The Sokoto State Government through the Ministry of Women and Children Affairs has intervened in the rescue of a 12-year-old girl allegedly caged and starved by her aunty. The victim, Joy, was reportedly caged in a condemned deep freezer and kept in a zinc house, by her aunt, Esther Emmanuel, in connivance with her husband, Bassey Emmanuel. She was said to have been subjected to that condition for eight months on the claim that she is mentally unstable. The police were invited by neighbours when they noticed the dehumanised condition of the girl and she was rescued. Immediately, the police rescued the girl, Sokoto State Commissioner for Women and Children Affairs, Hajiya Kulu Sifawa, in company of the state Police Commissioner, Kamaldeen Okunlola, and officials of the National Agency for the Prohibition of Trafficking in Persons visited the crime scene. Visiting the victim at the Sokoto State Specialists Hospital where she is receiving treatment, Sifawa said, “The state government is taking responsibility for treating the victim and ensuring she is properly recuperated.” She added, “Under this administration, there is no room for assault and violation of any kind against persons as the government is committed to fighting such an evil act.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com